For thermal conductivities, try this in Python:


from Cantera import *
gas = GRI30(&quot;Multi&quot;)
gas.set(T = 1200.0, P = OneAtm, X = &quot;CH4:1, O2:2&quot;)
print &#39;thermal conductivity = &#39;, gas.thermalConductivity(), &#39;W/m/K&#39;

On my Mac, the output produced is:

dgg:~&gt;python tcon.py
thermal conductivity =  0.126462420731 W/m/K

For a different T, P, and mole fractions, modify the &#39;set&#39; statement as 
needed.


Flame speed can be calculated in C++, but the Python / MATLAB functions 
needed to solve a freely propagating flame have not been put in yet.  
It should be in version 1.6 due out in January.

Dave



